<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="LGA Briefing" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment Food and Rural Affairs Select Committee inquiry into the future of flood and water management legislation</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from the Local Government Association [CST0012]</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice of local government.  We work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with councils to support, promote and improve local government.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA covers every part of England and Wales, supporting local government as the most efficient and accountable part of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> public sector.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The budgets of the police and their key partners as local authorities have been significantly reduced and will continue to reduce in the next few years. Deploying remaining resources in the most effective and efficient way is as a result very important. It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is therefore vital that local partners have accurate crime statistics if they are to respond to criminal activity in their area, commission services needed to prevent and reduce crime, and in particular respond to any emerging trends in the types of offen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ces being committed. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is clear from Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary (HMIC) inspections and reports in the last year that there are variations in recording by the police. This is to be expected given the judgements individual officers will ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve at the time they see an incident or based on the information they are given by the public when an incident is reported. The recording of offences related to anti-social behaviour remains more of an issue than in other crime types. As some forces clearly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have the leadership, practices and procedures in place that ensure crime statistics are accurate as they can be and as few crimes as possible are mis-recorded, greater use of the measures by these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> forces could be introduced in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all forces.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under-reporti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng and under-recording of crime remains an issue, which is why the Crime Survey for England and Wales is used as an alternative to police recorded crime to assess the actual levels of crime experienced by the public. For a range of crimes, such as those in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">volving offences committed against women and girls, increased reporting is desirable, and programmes seeking to address domestic abuse for example often seek to i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncrease reporting of incidents. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Greater consideration needs to be given to persuading the publ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic to report crime and how information from surveys of the public to assess levels of crime can be made available to local practitioners in a timely manner to assist them in planning and commissioning activity.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Crime statistics and local partnership activ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ity</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The police are not able to tackle crime effectively on their own. That is why close partnerships between the police and other local agencies like local authorities, fire and rescue services, probation and the health service are important. This partner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ship working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has in the LGA’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> view made a significant contribution to falling crime rates, whether recorded by the police or in the Crime Survey of England and Wales since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the mid-1990s. With local authority budgets being cut by 43 per cent by 2015/16, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd police budgets also reducing by a significant amount, local partners have to make the most effective and efficient use of remaining resources that they can. Decisions on what action to take, assessments of the effectiveness of particular courses of acti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on, and the commissioning of services to reduce crime and anti-social behaviour are all dependent on accurate crime statistics.   </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many partnerships have therefore had analytical capabilities in place to examine crime statistic trends and data and from th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is decide what action to take to address local issues - for example an increase in burglary rates in a particular locality or increases in shoplifting in town or city centres. The effectiveness and impact of operational decisions by local partners on a day</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to day, week to week, month to month and year to year basis can be seriously undermined if crime statistics are unreliable. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Accurate crime statistics also have an important role to play in the commissioning of services. Police and crime commissioners (P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCs) have been given specific funds in this financial year to commission services in their force area to reduce crime and anti-social behaviour. At the same time councils with their public health responsibilities have responsibility for commissioning servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ces locally that tackle health issues arising out of crime.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> clear understanding of what crime is being committed locally is vital if the correct commissioning decisions are to be made at a local level. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The existence of accurate crime statistics is impo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rtant locally for the additional reason that local scrutiny of performance rests on these statistics. Performance management by the police and partners organisations depends on having accurate statistics to gauge how well they are doing at meeting the obje</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ctives they have set themselves. The ability of crime and disorder scrutiny committees to judge the performance of their community safety partnership rests on accurate crime statistics. Similarly the ability of PCCs to hold chief constables to account for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the performance of their force relies on the PCC having access to crime statistics which help in throwing a light on how well the police locally are at tackling the issues they face. To an extent police and crime panels also need access to crime statistics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to enable them to judge how well the PCC is carrying out their role and holding the police to account. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The systems used for recording crime also need to be flexible enough and have enough different categories to identify emerging issues. The LGA has been involved in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">campaigning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for and then implementing new legislation to tackle metal theft. An early issue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with this particular crime was identifying the level of the problem due to the way such crimes were recorded under theft categories as there was no specific metal theft category. Even with a relevant category</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there continue to be issues over recording due</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the motivation for some thefts which could count as metal theft but the theft may have recorded as being for other more relevant reasons. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Early identification of emerging crime types also allows local partners to take more effective action earlier to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> address the causes of the problem. Work the Jill Dando Institute at University College London has recently carried out as a result of funding by the LGA and councils in the larger cities in England has identified mobile phone thefts as one of the crime ty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pes where rates are increasing. As a result the councils and police forces involved are already sharing and exploring what practice can help to reduce mobile phone thefts. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Committee should also therefore be considering as part of its inquiry whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local partnerships can have confidence in crime statistics and can rely on them to make operational decisions around activity they should be undertaking, and use the information from them to commission services.   </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Variations in recording of crime</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Committee sets out in the background to the inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is difficult to standardise the way that forces record offences. In fact it is difficult to standardise the way individual officers record offences even within the same force because of the huge vari</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ety in incidents they are faced with and the range of factors that may be of relevance in an incident. These difficulties were raised in HMIC’s review of police crime and incident reports published in 2012. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The HMIC report recorded a wide variation in po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lice forces’ quality when recording crime. Eighteen forces correctly recorded crime in 95 per cent of cases, fifteen did so in between 90 and 94 per cent of cases, and eleven forces in between 86 and 89 per cent of cases. There was also variability in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accuracy of decisions where it is recorded that no crime had been committed. In some forces 100 per cent of recorded decisions that there had been no crime were appropriate, but in the lowest performing forces only 75 per cent of decisions that there had b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">een no crime were appropriately recorded. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An area of particular variation was how accurately crime was recorded from incidents of anti-social behaviour (ASB), and whether repeat or vulnerable victims were identified early on. This of course has implicati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons for reducing instances of repeat victimisation, especially of vulnerable victims, that all local partners are keen to see happen, and which is behind the government’s proposal for a community trigger in the Anti-Social Beha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">viour, Crime and Policing Bill. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The HMIC report suggests improving the recording of crime information from ASB incidents could have a greater impact on identification of repeat incidents of ASB with vulnerable victims than the introduction of mechanisms li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ke the community trigger. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The HMIC report identified good leadership, coherent polices, effective systems and good performance management as being important factors in determining the quality of recorded crime information. Alongside a lead from the chief</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> constable and senior management in the force about properly recording crime, HMIC stated there needs to be a process of auditing and quality assuring data to assess how accurately crime is being recorded. With only half of forces making effective use of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heir crime audit results there is clearly scope for improvement. With PCCs now in place and as highlighted earlier needing accurate crime statistics to hold the police to account, there is a role for them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the LGA’s view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in helping to drive improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s in those forces where performance is not as good as it could be. Bringing the poorer performing forces up to the level of the best would drive a further improvement in the recording of crime statistics. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Under-reporting and under-recording of crime</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e other reason that the Committee identified for under-recording of crime is the fact that the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for a variety of reasons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> do not report crimes. This is the reason for the separate Crime Survey of England and Wales as a mechanism for identifying the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level of crime experienced by the public but not reported to the police. There are a number of offences that continue to be under-reported and therefore under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recorded. This is particularly the case for example with crimes that involve violence against wom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en and girls, such as domestic abuse. The lack of reporting of criminal incidents means that victims are not supported and the offenders escape detection. In cases of domestic abuse it is highly likely that the perpetrator has already been involved in repe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at offending for some time before a victim first reports them. The lack of reporting also makes it more difficult for local partners to judge the prevalence of a particular type of crime and how effective measures to address it are. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alongside better reco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rding of crime, there also needs to be more reporting of crime. That would assist local partners in identifying priorities and changes in crime trends. More needs to be done by both central government and local agencies to encourage greater reporting of cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ime by the public. This will not capture every crime as there will always be reasons why people do not report every criminal incident. The on-going use of surveys will need to supplement reporting and recording of crime into the future. However there are d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elays in the current publication of such information which continues to be at a national level. Having more frequent surveys which are published sooner after they are conducted could provide local agencies and partnerships with useful additional informatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n on which to basis commissioning decisions and also assess the effectiveness of some operational work.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>